content.Text:
[Tue 2026-04-21 16:50 PDT] Add a "Smart Customer Lifetime Value (CLV) Dashboard" to this ASP.NET MVC video rental app. This is an autonomous feature that predicts customer lifetime value based on rental history, segments customers by value tier, and provides proactive recommendations for value optimization.

## Architecture Pattern
Follow the exact pattern of existing features like ChurnPredictor:
- Service: `Vidly/Services/CustomerLifetimeValueService.cs`
- Controller: `Vidly/Controllers/CustomerLifetimeValueController.cs`
- View: `Vidly/Views/CustomerLifetimeValue/Index.cshtml`

## Models (in Vidly/Models/CustomerLifetimeValue.cs)
```csharp
namespace Vidly.Models
{
    public class ClvSummary
    {
        public decimal TotalEstimatedClv { get; set; }
        public decimal AverageClv { get; set; }
        public decimal MedianClv { get; set; }
        public int TotalCustomers { get; set; }
        public int WhaleCount { get; set; }  // Top tier
        public int HighValueCount { get; set; }
        public int MidValueCount { get; set; }
        public int AtRiskCount { get; set; }  // Low CLV + declining
        public List<ClvCustomerProfile> TopCustomers { get; set; }
        public List<ClvCustomerProfile> AtRiskCustomers { get; set; }
        public List<ClvRecommendation> Recommendations { get; set; }
        public List<ClvTierBreakdown> TierBreakdown { get; set; }
        public ClvTrend Trend { get; set; }
    }

    public class ClvCustomerProfile
    {
        public int CustomerId { get; set; }
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public string Email { get; set; }
        public MembershipType Membership { get; set; }
        public decimal EstimatedClv { get; set; }
        public decimal HistoricalRevenue { get; set; }
        public decimal PredictedFutureRevenue { get; set; }
        public int TotalRentals { get; set; }
        public decimal AvgMonthlySpend { get; set; }
        public int MonthsActive { get; set; }
        public string Tier { get; set; }  // Whale, High, Mid, Low
        public string Trajectory { get; set; }  // Rising, Stable, Declining
        public decimal RetentionProbability { get; set; }
        public List<string> ValueDrivers { get; set; }
    }

    public class ClvTierBreakdown
    {
        public string Tier { get; set; }
        public int Count { get; set; }
        public decimal TotalClv { get; set; }
        public decimal AvgClv { get; set; }
        public decimal RevenueShare { get; set; }  // percentage
        public string Color { get; set; }
    }

    public class ClvRecommendation
    {
        public string Type { get; set; }  // Upsell, Retain, Reactivate, Reward
        public string Priority { get; set; }  // High, Medium, Low
        public string Title { get; set; }
        public string Description { get; set; }
        public int AffectedCustomers { get; set; }
        public decimal EstimatedImpact { get; set; }
    }

    public class ClvTrend
    {
        public List<string> Labels { get; set; }  // Month labels
        public List<decimal> AvgClvOverTime { get; set; }
        public List<decimal> NewCustomerClv { get; set; }
    }
}
```

## Service (Vidly/Services/CustomerLifetimeValueService.cs)
- Constructor takes ICustomerRepository, IRentalRepository, IMovieRepository (same pattern as ChurnPredictorService)
- `GetSummary(DateTime now, int topN = 15)` - returns ClvSummary
- `GetCustomerProfile(int customerId, DateTime now)` - returns single ClvCustomerProfile
- CLV Calculation: Historical revenue + predicted future value based on:
  - Average monthly spend × predicted remaining months (based on membership tenure patterns)
  - Retention probability (higher for longer-tenure, higher-tier members)
  - Recency weighting (recent activity = higher predicted future value)
- Tier assignment: Whale (top 10%), High (10-30%), Mid (30-70%), Low (bottom 30%)
- Trajectory: compare last 3 months spend to previous 3 months
- Generate proactive recommendations (at least 5-6) based on analysis
- Use `using System; using System.Collections.Generic; using System.Linq; using Vidly.Models; using Vidly.Repositories;`

## Controller (Vidly/Controllers/CustomerLifetimeValueController.cs)
```csharp
// Same pattern as ChurnPredictorController
// GET: CustomerLifetimeValue → Index view with summary
// GET: CustomerLifetimeValue/Customer/5 → JSON with individual profile
// GET: CustomerLifetimeValue/Export → JSON export of all data
```

## View (Vidly/Views/CustomerLifetimeValue/Index.cshtml)
Full standalone HTML page (Layout = null) with dark theme matching existing dashboards (#0f1419 bg, #192734 cards, #2d3741 borders).

Include:
1. **Summary cards row**: Total CLV, Avg CLV, Whale count, At-Risk count, Trend arrow
2. **CLV Distribution donut chart** (Canvas) showing tier breakdown with colors: Whale=#9b59b6, High=#1da1f2, Mid=#17bf63, Low=#8899a6
3. **CLV Trend line chart** (Canvas) showing avg CLV over last 6 months
4. **Top Customers table**: sortable, with tier badges, trajectory arrows, CLV bar
5. **At-Risk Customers panel**: customers with declining trajectory
6. **Proactive Recommendations panel**: cards with priority badges, impact estimates
7. **Customer detail modal** (fetch via AJAX to /CustomerLifetimeValue/Customer/{id})

Use inline CSS/JS, no external dependencies. Make it interactive with click handlers. Use Canvas API for charts.

Back link: `<a href="/Dashboard" class="back-link">← Dashboard</a>`

After creating all files, run: `dotnet build --no-restore -q Vidly.sln` to verify it compiles. Fix any errors before finishing.
